üìù UPDATE Statement in MySQL
The UPDATE command is used to modify existing records in a table. You can update one or multiple columns in a single query.

‚úÖ Update a Single Column
Syntax:
    UPDATE <table_name>
    SET column_name = new_value
    WHERE condition;

Example:
    UPDATE stud_info
    SET COURSE = 'MCA'
    WHERE id = 1;

‚úÖ Update Multiple Columns
Syntax:
    UPDATE <table_name>
    SET column_name1 = new_value1,
        column_name2 = new_value2
    WHERE condition;

Example:
    UPDATE stud_info
    SET COURSE = 'MCA',
        NAME = 'RAMA'
    WHERE id = 1;

üíª Practical Example
üõ†Ô∏è Create and View Table
    CREATE TABLE EMP_INFO (
        ID INT,
        NAME VARCHAR(20),
        JDATE DATE,
        SALARY FLOAT
    );

    DESC EMP_INFO;

üì• Insert Sample Records
    INSERT INTO EMP_INFO VALUES
    (1, 'Ram', '2019-10-22', 25000),
    (2, 'Raju', '2020-08-12', 15500),
    (3, 'Ravi', '2018-07-28', 28000),
    (4, 'Rahul', '2018-02-21', 75000);

    SELECT * FROM EMP_INFO;

‚ùì Queries
üî∏ Q1: Add 3300 to all employee salaries
    SET SQL_SAFE_UPDATES = 0; -- (Optional: disables safe update mode)
    UPDATE EMP_INFO SET SALARY = SALARY + 3300;

    SELECT * FROM EMP_INFO;

üî∏ Q2: Update Raju's salary to 23000
    UPDATE EMP_INFO
    SET SALARY = 23000
    WHERE NAME = 'Raju';

    SELECT * FROM EMP_INFO;

üî∏ Q3: Add 1500 to salary of employee who joined on 2020-08-12
    UPDATE EMP_INFO
    SET SALARY = SALARY + 1500
    WHERE JDATE = '2020-08-12';

    SELECT * FROM EMP_INFO;

üî∏ Q4: Add 2100 to salaries of employees earning less than 27000
    UPDATE EMP_INFO
    SET SALARY = SALARY + 2100
    WHERE SALARY < 27000;

    SELECT * FROM EMP_INFO;
